Short reflection (300–500 words) answering:

What was your game idea?
My game idea was inspired by the well-known dinosaur game that appears in Google Chrome when there is no internet connection. 
In my version of the game, the main character is a person who jumps over cars instead of a dinosaur jumping over cacti. 
The main concept of the game is very simple: the player taps the screen or presses a button to make the character 
jump and avoid incoming cars. If the player fails to jump in time and hits a car, the game ends. I wanted to create 
something simple but still engaging, similar to many casual mobile games where the objective is to survive for as long as 
possible while the speed gradually increases.

What was the most difficult part to implement?
The most difficult part for me was putting my idea into reality. Even though the concept of the game seemed simple in my head, 
implementing it in the actual development environment was much more challenging. I had to think about how to make the character jump 
properly, how the cars would appear and move toward the player, and how to detect collisions between the character and the cars. 
There were also challenges related to organizing the code and making sure that different parts of the game worked together smoothly. 
At times, it was difficult to translate my idea into actual game mechanics and programming logic, especially since I am still learning 
mobile development tools.

What would you improve with more time?
If I had more time to improve the game, I would focus on enhancing the game mechanics and improving the user interface (UI). For example, 
I would like to make the movement smoother and add more variety to the obstacles so the game becomes more interesting over time. 
I would also improve the visual design of the game, such as adding better graphics, animations, and sound effects. Additionally, I would 
redesign the user interface to make it more appealing and easier for players to understand. Features like a score system, a restart 
button, and possibly different levels or difficulty settings could also make the game more enjoyable. With more time and practice, I 
believe the game could become more polished and provide a better experience for players.
